## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

### Critical Issues in the Original Code

| Issue | Severity | Details |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | 🔴 **Breaking** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | 🟡 Deprecated pattern | Works but unreliable for `WaitOne()` wake-up |
| **Race condition** | 🔴 **Bug** | Multiple `Enqueue` calls → one `Reset` → items lost in queue |
| Manual `lock` + `Queue` | 🟡 Unnecessary | Modern primitives handle this |
| No cancellation | 🟡 Design gap | No cooperative shutdown mechanism |

### The Race Condition Explained

```
Thread A: Enqueue("a") → Set()
Thread B: Enqueue("b") → Set()    // already set, no-op
Worker:   WaitOne() → Reset() → Dequeue("a") → Handle("a")
Worker:   WaitOne()  ← BLOCKS FOREVER. "b" is stuck in queue.
```

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();          // signals no more items
        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            using var delayCts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout.Value);
            try
            {
                await _workerTask.WaitAsync(delayCts.Token);
            }
            catch (TimeoutException)
            {
                // Worker didn't finish draining in time — cancel it
                _cts?.Cancel();
                await _workerTask.WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(1));
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

### Key Migration Decisions

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` + `Queue` | `Channel<T>` | Thread-safe, backpressure-aware, no race condition |
| `new Thread(...)` | `Task.Run(...)` | Uses thread pool; avoids orphaned threads |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` | Cooperative cancellation — the only supported model |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Channel.Writer.Complete()` | Clean signal to stop reading |
| Fire-and-forget `void` | `async Task` + `IAsyncDisposable` | Proper lifecycle and error observability |

### Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`Thread.Abort()` silently breaks** — it compiles fine but throws at runtime. Search your codebase for all `Abort()` calls.

2. **`Handle()` exceptions** — in the original code, an exception kills the thread silently. Add a `try/catch` inside the loop if `Handle` can throw:
   ```csharp
   await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
   {
       try { Handle(item); }
       catch (Exception ex) { Log(ex); }
   }
   ```

3. **Bounded vs. Unbounded** — `CreateUnbounded` matches the original `Queue` behavior (unlimited growth). For production, prefer `CreateBounded<string>(capacity)` to apply backpressure.

4. **Sync callers** — if your callers can't go async, wrap `StopAsync`:
   ```csharp
   public void Stop() => StopAsync().GetAwaiter().GetResult();
   ```
   But prefer propagating `async` up the call stack.
